title.narrative: SWAp for Parana Multi-sector Development Project

description.narrative: The objectives of the Project are to: (i) increase the survival rate in the final cycle of fundamental education; (ii) improve maternal and emergency health care services; (iii) promote business initiatives and improve natural resources management in rural areas; and (iv) contribute to building capacity in public administration, and environmental and disaster risk management.

condition.narrative: Finance Agreement :Change of mid-term review from 18 months to 25 months after effectiveness | Description :Finance Agreement:Schedule 2, Section I.C.5 | The Borrower shall not later than 25 months after the Effective Date, carry out a mid-term review withthe Bank on the overall progress in the execution of Part 1 of the Project and on the accomplishment of said Part of the Projectand shall agree with the Bank whether it will be necessary to modify any existing DLIs or incorporate new ones. | | Due Date:31-Mar-2016

Finance Agreement :Schedule 2, Section I.A.1 (a) | Description :No later than two (2) months after the Effective Date, the Borrowershall create and thereafter operate and maintain, until the completion of the Project:(a) a coordination unit within SEPL, to beresponsible for the overall coordination of the Project (the “PCU”). | Due Date :28-Feb-2014

Finance Agreement :Schedule 2, Section I.A.1 (b) | Description :No later than two (2) months after the Effective Date, the Borrowershall create and thereafter operate and maintain: (b) a ProjectManagement Committee, with representatives of all the ProjectSecretariats and Project Agencies involved in the Project to be responsible for overseeing implementation, monitoring andevaluation of all Project activities at least twice a year | Due Date :28-Feb-2014

Finance Agreement :Schedule 2, Section I.B.1 | Description :The Borrower shall, prior to initiating Project activities for which aParticipating Entity is responsible, and following the model in the Project Operational Manual, enter into separate implementationagreements (the Implementation Agreements), satisfactory to the Bank. | Due Date :31-Dec-2013

Finance Agreement :Schedule 2, Section I.C.1 | Description :The Borrower shall, through SEPL, furnish to the Bank on or aboutFebruary 28 and August 31 of each year, starting on the first such date after the Effective Date, regular reports (the EEP SpendingReports) prepared in accordance with the provisions of the Project Operational Manual and the additional instructions referred toin Section IV.A. of the Loan Agreement. | Frequency :SemiAnnual

Finance Agreement :Schedule 2, Section I.C.2 (b) | Description :The Borrower shall, through SEPL furnish to the Bank as soon asavailable, but in any case not later than six months after the endof each such calendar year, the procurement audit report of suchaudit by said auditors, of such scope and in such detail as the Bank shall have reasonably requested. | Frequency :Yearly

Finance Agreement :Schedule 2, Section I.C.3 | Description :The Borrower shall ensure that the budget code number indicated inSchedule 4 to the Loan Agreement shall conform to the Borrower'sannual budget law. | Frequency :Yearly

Finance Agreement :Schedule 2, Section I.C.4 | Description :The Borrower and the Bank may jointly review, once every year, theamounts assigned per budget code to the EEPs detailed in Schedule 4 to the Loan Agreement, and the Borrower shall adjust as neededthe budget amounts of any EEP with the prior written agreement ofthe Bank. | Frequency :Yearly

Finance Agreement :Schedule 2, Section I.E.1 | Description :The Borrower shall, through the Project Secretariats implement, & causethe Project Agencies & other Participating Entities, to implement the Project in accordance with the provisions of theEnvironmental Management Framework (EMF) (including with the provisions of each Environmental Management Plan) & the IndigenousPeoples Framework (including with the provisions of each Indigenous Peoples Plan) | Frequency :CONTINUOUS

title.narrative: Decrease in Mortality Rate for deaths through external causes, except violence
Decrease in Mortality Rate for Cardiovascular Diseases (by age group)
Management Plans for rural roads prepared

Number of Municipalities with a Decentralized Environmental Licensing and Monitoring System
Beneficiaries of legally concluded land regularization processes

Number of Farmers trained or receiving technical assistance

Hectares supported by the Micro-catchment Action Plans' interventions
University-based in-service Teacher Training, Education Development Plan (EDP)

Teachers participating in Peer-to-peer in-service Teacher Training

baseline.value: Internal Control Unit recently created and lacking formal methods and procedures

target.value: Internal control information system implemented and operational in 50 government entities

actual.value: Internal control information system implemented and operational in 117 government entities and 100% of users trained

title.narrative: Strengthening of the Disaster Risk Monitoring capacity and Warning System for Hydro-meteorological events

target.value: Increased capacity (qualitative and quantitative) of the Warning System, i.e. equipment, models, processes, among others

actual.value: Capacity (qualitative and quantitative) of the Warning System increased through new equipment and implementation of new models andprocesses

title.narrative: Establishment of State Disaster Risk Management (DRM) Policy Framework

baseline.value: Publication of State Decree establishing the DRM working group

target.value: State Plan for Protection and Civil Defense is under implementation.

actual.value: The State Plan for Protection and Civil Defense has been drafted and was presented to the state council for protection and civildefense in August 2016. However, the State Plan is dependent on the National Plan which has yet to be published.

title.narrative: Capacity strengthening of SEED to evaluate teacher training programs.

baseline.value: The capacity for teacher training evaluation is inadequate

target.value: Evaluation report on the implementation of the pedagogical intervention project (third dimension of the Educational DevelopmentPlan - PDE)

actual.value: Evaluation report on the implementation of the third dimension of the Educational Development Plan - PDE has not be prepared

title.narrative: Improved Management of Physical Infrastructures is schools for SEED

baseline.value: The management of physical infrastructure in the education sector is inadequate

target.value: Monitoring System for Physical Infrastructures is operational (implemented in SEED and the NREs)

actual.value: Monitoring System for Physical Infrastructures is operational

title.narrative: Strengthening State Capacity to monitor and evaluate public policies

baseline.value: Weak capacity to monitor and evaluate public policies

target.value: Report with recommendations on the sustainability and continuation of the land regularization activities.

actual.value: Report with recommendations on the sustainability and continuation of the land regularization activities.

title.narrative: Revenue from tax arrears as a share of the stock of tax arrears
Percentage of the population with access to Urgent and Emergency Health services
Indigenous lands with productive projects supported
Number of teachers who work in indigenous schools trained
Reduction of sick leave and absenteeism due to work-related illness or injury

baseline.value: The State has started to define an occupational health policy

target.value: Reduction of sick leaves/absences due to work-related illness or injury by 20%

actual.value: The implementation of occupational health activities is being done using own funds.

title.narrative: Implementation of a water resources subsystem of an Integrated Environmental and Water Resources Management System

baseline.value: No integrated environmental and water resource management system in place

target.value: Average processing time for issuing of water rights has been reduced to 90 days (from 180 in 2016)

actual.value: Three of the four modules of the subsystem are implemented

title.narrative: Enhancing core competencies of civil servants

baseline.value: No online training platform in place and need for additional training for civil servants

target.value: Competencies of civil servants have increased (as reported in the final report of the consultancy)

actual.value: Competencies of civil servants have increased

title.narrative: Improvement of the Borrower's tax management system

baseline.value: Lack of enforcement in tax arrears collection and adequate resources to administer tax receipts

target.value: Evaluation, declaration and collection of ITCMD is 90% automated

actual.value: Processes of restitution, rectification, and exemption and immunity requests are done through the integrated system.
